post_text:
Lodi USD:

The U.S. Department of Agriculture (USDA) passed a waiver allowing students under 18 to eat for free at any school site regardless of eligibility until the end of the year (or while funding is available).

This means all students can eat for free and younger siblings who are not Lodi USD students can also eat for free.

There will be no meal service tomorrow, September 7. Meal service will resume on Wednesday, September 9.

If you have not received a postcard for your child, please check with your child's school. Schools are still making and scanning cards for enrolled students.

For more info, please visit our Nutrition Services' website: https://bit.ly/3dBOshh.

National Preparedness Month (NPM) is recognized each September to promote family and community disaster planning now and throughout the year.

Stockton Police Department
August 11 at 10:18 AM ¬∑

SPD News: YES ‚Äì I want my voice heard

YES is the Stockton Police Department‚Äôs youth engagement strategy designed to further developing trust and relationships with our youth and young adults.

YES will partner with community youth programs and youth groups that serve Stockton youth, ages 14-18, coordinated and fueled by community volunteers. YES creates engagement and interaction opportunities with the Stockton Police Department while providing education, leadership, and community service opportunities.

Those participants of groups enrolled in YES that are interested in being ambassadors on the Youth Advisory Board can apply by completing the Youth Advisory Board Application by clicking on the below link.

For more information you may email the YES Program Manager, Lieutenant Craig Smith, at spdyes@stocktonca.gov.

http://ww1.stocktonca.gov/en/Departments/Police/Programs-and-Services/YES-Program

shared_text:
San Joaquin County Office of Education
July 23 at 6:09 PM ¬∑

Lodi Unified School District visited the SJCOE campus on Thursday to load up on PPE (personal protective equipment). Several large trucks picked up multiple pallets of supplies that will be delivered to individual school sites, available to students and staff when they return to campus.

The California Department of Education and the California Governor's Office of Emergency Services is distributing PPE and other supplies to schools through county offices of education throughout California. So far in San Joaquin County, that amounts to 36,600 bottles of hand sanitizer, 18,240 N95 respirator masks, 208,000 adult-size masks, 164,000 child-size masks, 24,480 plastic face shields, and 1,200 non-contact infrared thermometers for school districts and charter schools.

Lodi USD:

Tomorrow the Board of Education will hold a Special Meeting at 7PM on GoToWebinar to approve an agreement with the Lodi Education Association (LEA), the union that represents the teachers in our District, regarding All Distance Learning.

The Memorandum of Understanding (MOU) calls for a new start date for students of August 10, 2020, with an additional week added to the end of the 2020-21 school year.

We will continue to communicate with our families and staff regarding any official change to the 2020-21 school calendar.

To view the agenda for tomorrow evening, please visit https://bit.ly/30x0C5D.

shared_text:
10th Annual Teacher of the Year Celebration

San Joaquin County Office of Education premiered a video.
July 16 at 4:49 PM ¬∑

Please join us in watching the 10th Annual Teacher of the Year Celebration.

The emcee is SJCOE Assistant Superintendent of Educational Services Jane Steinkamp, who oversees the annual Teacher of the Year recognition program in the county and will introduce all five finalists during the video celebration.

She will be joined by San Joaquin County Superintendent of Schools James Mousalimas and Premier Community Credit Union CEO Russel Hagen, who will announce this San Joaquin County Teacher of the Year.

The San Joaquin County Teacher of the Year will be nominated as California Teacher of the Year and will receive $1,000 from Premier Community Credit Union. Each finalist receives $400.

Lodi USD:

This evening, the San Joaquin County Office of Education (SJCOE) and San Joaquin County Public Health Services (PHS) announced revised guidelines regarding the 2020-21 school year. Due to the rise in confirmed cases of COVID-19 and increased hospitalizations in San Joaquin County, PHS and SJCOE strongly recommend that schools begin the 2020-21 school year with all students on Distance Learning through at least the end of August, 2020.

Lodi USD Board Members have acknowledged that this health crisis continues to change and that we need to continue to be flexible throughout the school year.

The Board will discuss the revised guidelines tomorrow during their Board Meeting in order to give revised direction regarding the start of the school year. The Board Meeting will be available to the public on GoToWebinar and livestreamed on YouTube. There will be time for public comment.

Lodi USD Class of 2020 and Parents/Guardians:

We are very disappointed to share that we will not be able to host an in-person graduation for our Class of 2020.

Current health orders do not allow for us to hold this type of event in San Joaquin County and in order to adequately prepare for an in-person graduation, we were committed to a final decision by June 30.

Please know that this is not what we wanted for our Class of 2020 and we understand the disappointment this brings. We thank our schools and communities for their efforts to celebrate high school graduates in alternative ways and wish all of our graduates the very best.

Students are speaking out: They want to include the study of race, ethnicity and indigeneity in their classroom experience. As the CDE prepares to submit a revised Ethnic Studies Model Curriculum for public review, State Superintendent Tony Thurmond announced earlier today he will be launching an upcoming series of virtual ethnic studies webinars for students, educators, and families.

We're proud to announce that so far, participants include:

‚Ä¢ Civil Rights Activist Dolores Huerta
‚Ä¢ Assemblymember Shirley Weber, a Professor Emeritus and co-founder of Africana Studies at San Diego State University
‚Ä¢ Assemblymember Jose Medina, who drafted legislation to make ethnic studies a high school graduation requirement
‚Ä¢ Dr. Karen Korematsu, daughter of late civil rights icon Fred Korematsu

Stay tuned as we announce more details in the coming days!

June 20 at 12:14 PM ¬∑

In this meetup we will be looking at one of the common frameworks used today, Bootstrap. Matthew Hicks will explain why so many people use it, when it came about, and how to use it. San Joaquin County Public Health Services
June 19 at 11:06 AM ¬∑

PHS wishes you a Happy Juneteenth!

Juneteenth is the oldest nationally celebrated commemoration of the ending of slavery in the United States. It marks the anniversary of June 19,1865, the day that the Texan slaves found out they were freed by the Emancipation Proclamation two and a half years after it happened. For more information on Juneteenth, visit www.juneteenth.com/history.htm.

Please keep COVID-19 precautions in mind with all celebrations this weekend! CDC has the guidance: https://bit.ly/37I1uY4

State Superintendent Tony Thurmond announced today that the CDE, in collaboration with the San Diego County Office of Education, is launching a free online suicide prevention training program available to middle and high school staff and students throughout the state.

The online training program is called LivingWorks Start, an evidence-based program that is aligned with CDE‚Äôs Model Youth Suicide Prevention Policy to address the needs of high-risk populations. According to a recent report by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, suicide is the second leading cause of death for youth ages ten to twenty-four.

Read more: https://www.cde.ca.gov/nr/ne/yr20/yr20rel44.asp

California Department of Education
June 15 at 3:16 PM ¬∑

Students in the middle and high school age range are invited to attend "Student Support Circle: Institutional Racism and Implicit Bias" hosted by the CDE and State Superintendent Tony Thurmond, this Thursday, June 18 at 4 p.m, on Facebook Live. It's hosted in partnership with with National Equity Project, and will feature California Surgeon General Dr. Nadine Burke Harris.

It will also feature students from across the state speaking about what they've experienced and talk about practical solutions to institutional racism and implicit basis in public schools.

The CDE recently created an email address for our communities to have their voices heard regarding institutional racism. Please submit your ideas and feedback to createracialjustice@gmail.com.

San Joaquin County Office of Education
June 11 at 6:00 PM ¬∑

Three cheers for Laura La Rue, one of the five finalists for San Joaquin County Teacher of the year we are celebrating this week. This English teacher at Bear Creek High School (Lodi Unified School District) has been an educator for 23 years.

"What truly elevates Ms. La Rue as an exemplary teacher is her ability to meet the needs of all students," writes Bear Creek High Principal Hillary Harrell in her nomination. "Ms. La Rue monitors her students very closely throughout her instruction, and she adjusts it as necessary to meet their needs. Most teachers with her level of experience would not ask others for help, but Ms. La Rue continually asks for suggestions, especially for students who struggle."

Congratulations Laura La Rue!

We will continue to highlight San Joaquin County's Teacher of the Year nominees this week. The winner will be announced in the fall. The winning teacher will be the San Joaquin County nominee for the California Teacher of the Year.

June 8 at 9:07 AM ¬∑

Today, State Superintendent Tony Thurmond will release the CDE guidance document, ‚ÄúStronger Together: A Guidebook for the Safe Reopening of California‚Äôs Public Schools." During a news conference at 11:15 a.m. on Facebook Live, Thurmond and CDE leaders will walk through the document‚Äôs key tools and recommendations.

This guidance will serve as a road map of recommendations for schools as they work with their local public health officials and school communities to navigate next steps. Educational leaders will find recommendations for face coverings, physical distancing, and symptom screening should schools plan to provide some form of in-person instruction and distance learning. The document will also provide in-depth considerations for designing high-quality and equitable instructional practices for all students.

Lodi USD:

We are aware that a racially offensive video featuring students who attended Lodi High has recently resurfaced on social media. We want to be clear that we do not condone this behavior. When the video was originally brought to the attention of Lodi High‚Äôs administration in February 2020, law enforcement was immediately contacted and action was taken by Lodi High.

Our District has policies and practices in place to make sure that our students can learn and staff can work in an environment free from bullying, harassment, and discrimination. We are committed to providing a safe and welcoming environment for all students, parents, and staff and we greatly appreciate communication from our community regarding concerns and suggestions.

California Department of Education
June 4 at 11:10 AM ¬∑

State Superintendent Tony Thurmond will host a virtual media check-in today at 3 p.m. to provide updates on ways he and the CDE intend to lead ongoing initiatives to address implicit bias and racism in public education and beyond. It will be streamed here on Facebook Live.

On Monday, the State Superintendent responded to the death of George Floyd by calling on communities across the state and nation to take action to dismantle institutional racism and inequities in public schools. He invited students, educators, families, and partners to participate in honest, courageous conversations that can help inform the work ahead. Thurmond also intends to convene stakeholders in discussions of implicit bias beyond schools to include leaders of law enforcement organizations, elected officials, and civic leaders.

Lodi USD:

Children who are eligible for free or reduced-price meals are also eligible for Pandemic EBT (P-EBT) benefits and can get up to $365 per child in state benefits to buy food in addition to the pickup meals available at selected Lodi USD schools. Learn more about P-EBT and apply online at www.ca.p-ebt.org before June 30, 2020.

You can also still apply for free and reduced priced school meals before the end of June, even though school is not in session and have your benefits carry over for a 30 day grace period at the beginning of the 2020-2021 school year. Learn more and apply online at www.schoollunchapp.com.

#ClosedButCaring #TogetherApart

post_text:
Lodi USD:

The Board of Education recognizes the negative impact this global health crisis may have on many students, especially seniors preparing for graduation. Therefore, the Board approved the modification of certain graduation requirements for the class of 2020.

For the senior class of 2020:

‚óæÔ∏èThe 4 year English requirement is reduced to 3 years, which is in alignment with the state minimum requirement. This eliminates 10 credits of English.

‚óæÔ∏èThe Elective requirement is reduced by 10 credits.

The Board‚Äôs action lowered the minimum graduation requirement from 230 to 210 credits for the senior class of 2020. This remains within state requirements.

If you have any questions regarding the status of your senior‚Äôs graduation, please contact your school principal.

post_text:
Lodi USD:

At last night‚Äôs Board of Education Meeting, the Board gave approval to offer Summer School for 9th ‚Äì 12th grade students. Students can take classes for credit recovery and advancement. Classes will be structured in a Distance Learning model in order to adhere to health guidelines. The online student enrollment process is open until Friday, May 15. We look forward to this new approach to Summer School.

As you are aware, Governor Newsom has been talking about his plan to reopen businesses and services and has stated that schools might start July or August. Please understand that no decisions have been made at this point; however, we are working on plans for different scenarios. Of course, what school will look like for the opening of the 2020-2021 school year will depend on orders and guidelines from state and health officials. Our Distance Learning Task Force groups are discussing ideas and we will ask for your input through Thoughtexchange. We will share the ideas and input with the Board of Education at an upcoming Board Meeting.

post_text:
Lodi USD:

A message went out today about this year‚Äôs summer school. It has come to our attention that this has caused concern and that clarification is needed.

‚è∫Direction for summer school was given by District leadership staff, not the Board of Education.

‚è∫The model mirrors what the District offered in the past as a result of budget concerns.

‚è∫Summer school has not been eliminated.

‚è∫The current plan is to offer credit recovery for this year‚Äôs 11th and 12th grade students to give them opportunities to meet graduation requirements.

‚è∫Concerns have been expressed regarding Government/Economics as many students take this opportunity in order to take other classes during the regular school year. This addition is being considered.

‚è∫The Board of Education will review the expenditures associated with summer school and determine offerings at a Special Board of Education Meeting (virtual) on Thursday, May 7, 2020. Open session begins at 7:15 P.M.

We will communicate any Board decision to our staff and community.
